issue.title: Lps 123151
issue.body:
__Ticket:__
<https://issues.liferay.com/browse/LPS-123151>

Hi @hhuijser,

This is a new source format rule @kevhlee has worked on. I believe it looks good, but we wanted to get a look from you before it gets sent to Brian. Please let us know if there are any thoughts or concerns.

Original Notes from @kevhlee:
> __Notes__:
> This SF rule does the following:
> * Ensure that the column field names match the ones in the corresponding upgrade table class, if the class exists.
>  * Only use the following data types: `BLOB`, `SBLOB`, `BOOLEAN`, `DATE`, `DOUBLE`, `INTEGER`, `LONG`, `STRING`, `TEXT`, `VARCHAR` (see [`BaseDB.java`](https://github.com/liferay/liferay-portal/blob/master/portal-impl/src/com/liferay/portal/dao/db/BaseDB.java#L845-L849)).
>  * When using string data types (`VARCHAR`, `STRING`, `TEXT`), we must specify whether they are nullable or not by appending `null` or `not null`.
> 
> One thing to note is that the SF rule uses the upgrade table class, __NOT__ the module's `service.xml`, to verify column names. @achaparro and I had a discussion about using the `service.xml` to verify the column names rather using the table upgrade class, since table upgrade classes will no longer be needed in the future ([LPS-134196](https://issues.liferay.com/browse/LPS-134196)). However, using only the module's `service.xml` can be problematic as column fields are removed from `service.xml` from time to time. So when we apply SF to the older upgrade processes that use column names that no longer exist in `service.xml`, false SF errors can be generated.

issue.title: Naming observations
issue.body:
Looking at the connectome DB I am wondering what we can do about more convenient naming. Here is a log:

I browse on the web and click on `MGH HCP Adult Diffusion`.

A subheading on the next page show `Dataset ID: MGH_DIFF`, which is conveniently enough to compose:

```
datalad xnat-init --credential connectomedb https://db.humanconnectome.org -p MGH_DIFF
```

when I want to download a specific subject, I click on "Browse subjects" and see IDs like `MGH_1001`. However these are not the subject IDs used internally, which are of format `ConnectomeDB_S01...`.

I can reveal these IDs by clicking on a subject, and they are listed as

```
Accession ID: ConnectomeDB_S01...
```

Confusingly, the same page also states

```
Project: MGH HCP Diffusion | MGH_1001
```

but "MGH HCP Diffusion" is actually a link to `MGH_DIFF` (so name -> ID)

So bottomline: XNAT/ConnectomeDB often lists names, where we require IDs, and these IDs are embedded in the links behind the name, but are not immediately visible.

This is at least something to address in the documentation.

issue.title: [Question] Format for Unicode property escape test suite?
issue.body:
As part of my work on [the Unicode property escapes in regular expressions proposal](https://github.com/tc39/proposal-regexp-unicode-property-escapes), I’m planning to contribute tests for this feature. (Ref. https://github.com/tc39/proposal-regexp-unicode-property-escapes/issues/4.)

[My plan was to create a script (hosted in its own, separate repo)](https://github.com/mathiasbynens/unicode-property-escapes-tests) that generates the tests based on a given Unicode version, so they could easily be updated + upstreamed to test262. (Note that the Unicode standard is updated every year, and thus, so should the tests.) I would be maintaining this script and submitting PRs with the updated tests to test262 every year.

Now, because these tests will be generated programmatically, they can be as exhaustive as we want them to be. We can do better than randomly testing a couple of properties and symbols, which doesn’t guarantee 100% spec compliance. Ideally, every Unicode symbol would be tested against every supported property escape. This would ensure 100% interoperability (assuming all major engines run tests262 tests). The downside would be that these tests would potentially take a long time to run. @syg, @tcare: thoughts?

Here’s an exhaustive list of the supported properties per this proposal (as per the current version): https://github.com/mathiasbynens/regexpu-core/blob/master/property-escapes.md

My questions:

1. Would such a test suite make sense as part of test262?
2. If so, what would the directory/file structure look like? Some options:
    - A separate `*.js` file for each individual property escape?
    - A separate file for every `0xFFFF` code points (i.e. every Unicode plane)?
    - Is there a better idea?

Any feedback is welcome.

cc @leobalter @jugglinmike @littledan

issue.title: [question] Is it OK if I distribute freely a docker image with a fully set-up Cross-Lib enviroment including Z88DK?
issue.body:
Cross-Lib depends on 
more than a dozen cross-compilers 
https://github.com/Fabrizio-Caruso/CROSS-LIB/blob/master/docs/COMPILERS.md, 
a native compiler, make, python and few other tools.

Could I create a docker image with a fully set-up Cross-Lib environment (including Z88DK) and distribute it freely?
Obviously I would include links to the Z88DK and all the other compilers.
Cross-Lib is a totally free (for non-commercial use) and open source project.

This would make Cross-Lib so much easier to use for other people.

comment.body: Having a docker container image would be nice. In absence of one, [I am forced to build one myself](https://github.com/the-channels/channels/blob/master/Dockerfile#L8).
